{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff/composition: collectors -> aggregator -> summary input payload. A unit test of one function can miss wiring mistakes (e.g., one source dropped during orchestration). Higher levels were considered and rejected: System is disqualified because behavior text only requires verifying payload composition, not real HTTP/subprocess/OS effects; Agentic is disqualified because it checks pre-LLM input content, not model output quality; Workflow is disqualified because no multi-agentic sequence is required.","test_description":"Wire real report-orchestration modules with stubbed source clients returning distinct fixtures for metrics/issues/deployments; run one report build and assert the exact payload sent to summary generation contains all three source sections/keys.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test explicitly needs cross-module wiring and stays below real infra/model dependence.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is resilience across modules (source adapter error -> report assembler fallback note -> pipeline continues). Unit is too low because the bug can appear at exception propagation boundaries. Higher levels rejected: System is disqualified because unavailability can be reproduced by in-process client exception/timeout stubs without real network; Agentic is disqualified because correctness is fallback handling, not model judgment; Workflow is disqualified because no multi-agentic chain is specified.","test_description":"Run report generation with two source stubs returning data and one stub raising a fetch error; assert execution completes, report contains `data unavailable` in the failed section, and other sections are still populated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Covers real failure mode at module interfaces with no required real OS/network/model.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model output quality (factual fidelity to input values). Mocked/stubbed summaries would hide real hallucination/omission/paraphrase errors and always pass deterministic fixtures. Workflow rejected: behavior text describes one summary-generation decision, not multiple agentic stages in sequence.","test_description":"Use representative real input datasets and call the real summary-generation model; assert extracted key values/facts in output match source data within defined fidelity criteria over repeated runs/tolerance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real model behavior; lower deterministic tests cannot catch this class of failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.76,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary includes real external I/O: end-to-end collection plus actual email transport/inbox delivery. In-process mocks can hide SMTP/provider/auth/delivery-path failures. Agentic was considered and rejected as minimum because this behavior validates end-to-end delivery success, not summary quality; real model output content is not required to detect inbox-delivery failures. Workflow rejected because only one possible agentic step is implied, not a multi-agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Execute the scheduled/report pipeline against reachable test endpoints and a real test mailbox; verify message is delivered to configured recipient inbox with expected report artifact and no pipeline abort.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Requires real HTTP/email infrastructure to catch delivery-path failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure is orchestration/state handoff: send failure -> durable local persistence -> next-run retry logic. This can be caught with real local filesystem plus controlled sender failure in-process. Higher levels considered: System rejected because behavior text does not require validating real SMTP/network failure semantics, only fallback+retry behavior; Agentic rejected because no model-output dependence; Workflow rejected because no multi-agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Run pipeline with email sender stub failing first run and succeeding second run; use real temp filesystem storage; assert report file is written on failure, loaded on next run, retried, and cleared/marked delivered after success.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Uses minimum infra (module wiring + real local persistence) needed for this fallback state-transition failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.38,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}}]}
